<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-24T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-24T09:00:00-05:00" n="462" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d462">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4379: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-24T15:00:00+01:00">February 24, 1932—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 24—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>36. Addendum to my 35. <persName corresp="#p_SN1">Sato</persName> also
                            mentioned their growing feeling of apprehension at the isolation in
                            which Japan found itself and their especial anxiety caused by the
                            evidences of changing sentiment in the United States as shown by the
                            desire of peaceable-minded people to advocate an economic boycott.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_WHR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>